trans-unit.source: The search field is used for centering the map on a specific ship.
trans-unit.target: Sökfältet används för att centrera kartan på ett specifikt fartyg.

trans-unit.source: You can search ships by name in this field and once you have chosen the desired ship in the dropdown the map will center around that ship. The dropdown is sorted alphabetically and shows the top 10 results.
trans-unit.target: Du kan söka på fartyg i detta fältet och när du har valt fartyg i listan kommer kartan att centreras på ditt valda fartyg. Listan är sorterad i alfabetisk ordning och visar dom 10 bästa resultaten.

trans-unit.source: The search will try to find any ship containing that letter combination. For example the search query as will give you ships such as Askungen but also ships like Basto.
trans-unit.target: Sökningen förösöker hitta alla fartyg som innehåller den bokstavskombinationen Till exempel kommer sökningen as att ge dig fartyg som Askungen men också fartyg som Basto.

trans-unit.source: By starting with an exlamation mark the search will instead try to find any ship not containing the given text. I.e !as will give the reverse result.
trans-unit.target: By starting with an exlamation mark the search will instead try to find any ship not containing the given text. I.e !as will give the reverse result.

trans-unit.source: By starting your command with /c you can go directly to a specific cordinate. Example: /c 58.43562 17.45620
trans-unit.target: Ange /c för att komma till en specifik koordinat. Exempel: /c 58.43562 17.45620

trans-unit.source: The filter field is used for filtering ships that will be shown on the map. Just like the search function it will try to find any ship with the text in the name per default.
trans-unit.target: The filter field is used for filtering ships that will be shown on the map. Just like the search function it will try to find any ship with the text in the name per default.

trans-unit.source: By starting with an exlamation mark the filter will instead try to find any ship not containing the given text. Will only work on searches of type string.
trans-unit.target: By starting with an exlamation mark the filter will instead try to find any ship not containing the given text. Will only work on searches of type string.

trans-unit.source:
By starting with /f the filter will instead filter on flagstate. Type: string Examples:
/f swe will give you all swedish ships. /f swe,dnk will give you all swedish and danish ships. /f !swe,dnk will give you all ships that are not swedish or danish.
trans-unit.target:
By starting with /f the filter will instead filter on flagstate. Type: string Examples:
/f swe will give you all swedish ships. /f swe,dnk will give you all swedish and danish ships. /f !swe,dnk will give you all ships that are not swedish or danish.

trans-unit.source: By starting with /i the filter will instead filter on ircs. Type: string
trans-unit.target: By starting with /i the filter will instead filter on ircs. Type: string

trans-unit.source: By starting with /c the filter will instead filter on cfr. Type: string
trans-unit.target: By starting with /c the filter will instead filter on cfr. Type: string

trans-unit.source: By starting with /v the filter will instead filter on vessel type. Type: string
trans-unit.target: By starting with /v the filter will instead filter on vessel type. Type: string

trans-unit.source: By starting with /e the filter will instead filter on external marking. Type: string
trans-unit.target: By starting with /e the filter will instead filter on external marking. Type: string

trans-unit.source:
By starting with /l the filter will instead filter on ship length. Type: number Examples:
/l 9.23 will give you all ships with the exact length of 9.23 meters. /l 9 will give you all ships with the exact length of 9.00 meters. /f ~9 will give you all ships that have a length between 9 and 10 meters, i.e. 9, 9.55, 9.99 and so forth. /f >9 will give you all ships that have a length above 9 meters, i.e. 10, 19.23, 45.72 and so forth. /f <9 will give you all ships that have a length below 9 meters, i.e. 8.99, 7 and so forth. /f <9,>25 will give you all ships that have a length below 9 meters or above 25 meters.
trans-unit.target:
By starting with /l the filter will instead filter on ship length. Type: number Examples:
/l 9.23 will give you all ships with the exact length of 9.23 meters. /l 9 will give you all ships with the exact length of 9.00 meters. /f ~9 will give you all ships that have a length between 9 and 10 meters, i.e. 9, 9.55, 9.99 and so forth. /f >9 will give you all ships that have a length above 9 meters, i.e. 10, 19.23, 45.72 and so forth. /f <9 will give you all ships that have a length below 9 meters, i.e. 8.99, 7 and so forth. /f <9,>25 will give you all ships that have a length below 9 meters or above 25 meters.

trans-unit.source:
Is a separator, by using it you can filter on multiple things. All arguments given to the filter must be true for the ships to be visible. Examples:
/f swe & ask will give you all swedish ships that have ask in the name. ask & /f swe,dnk will give you all swedish and danish ships that have ask in the name. !ask & /f swe,dnk will give you all swedish and danish ships that dosn't have ask in the name. /l >10 & /l <20 will give you all ships that's bigger then 10 meters and smaller then 20 meters.
trans-unit.target:

trans-unit.source:
You can save screen locations, both zoom level and center position using the save slots. By pressing the alt-key and a number you can save your location to that number-key. To go to that location again you just press the number you saved to again. Examples:
Press alt + 1. You now have your current location saved to key 1. Press 1 You will now return the the saved location of 1 Press alt + 9 You now have your current location saved to key 9.
trans-unit.target:
